 memories that the Iskut share have been maintained orally. McIlwraith demonstrates the ways in which these stories challenge the idealized images of Aboriginals that underlie state-sponsored traditional ecological knowledge (TEK) studies. McIlwraith instead illuminates how these narratives are connected to the Iskut Village&apos;s complex relationships with resource extraction companies and the province of British Columbia, as well as their interactions with animals and the environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aOral historyzBritish ColumbiazIskut. 0aTahltan IndiansxHuntingzBritish ColumbiazIskutxHistory. 0aTahltan IndianszBritish ColumbiazIskutxHistory. 0aTraditional ecological knowledgezBritish ColumbiazIskut. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269570240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442695702423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442695702/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK